# config/ubuntu_bloat.list
# List of packages commonly considered "bloatware" for standard Ubuntu (GNOME) installations.
# Each package name should be on a new line.
# Lines starting with '#' are comments and will be ignored by the script.
#
# WARNING: Removing system packages can have unintended consequences.
# Review this list carefully before running the debloater script.
# If you are unsure about a package, it's safer to leave it commented out or remove it from the list.

# --- Office and Productivity ---
libreoffice-common
libreoffice-calc
libreoffice-draw
libreoffice-impress
libreoffice-math
libreoffice-writer
thunderbird

# --- Games ---
gnome-mahjongg
gnome-mines
gnome-sudoku
aisleriot
quadrapassel
hitori
lightsoff
swell-foop

# --- Internet and Communication (if not used) ---
remmina
remmina-plugin-vnc
remmina-plugin-secret
remmina-plugin-rdp
rhythmbox

# --- Multimedia and Graphics (if not used) ---
cheese
gnome-characters
shotwell
totem
simple-scan

# --- System Utilities (review carefully, some might be useful) ---
# NOTE: The following packages should NOT be removed as they are essential for system functionality:
# gnome-disk-utility - Essential disk management utility, removing can break disk operations
# gnome-system-monitor - Critical system monitoring tool, removing can affect system management
# yelp - Help documentation viewer, some system apps depend on it
# apport/apport-gtk/whoopsie - Core crash reporting system, removing can cause system instability
gnome-font-viewer
gnome-todo
popularity-contest # Sends anonymous usage statistics

# --- Accessibility (only remove if you don't need any accessibility features) ---
# NOTE: Accessibility packages have been removed from this list as they can break
# important functionality for users who need them, and some applications may
# depend on them. Only advanced users should consider removing these manually.
# gnome-orca
# orca
# brltty - Braille display driver (can cause USB serial port issues if removed)
# speech-dispatcher and related packages - required by some applications

# --- Other ---
example-content # Example documents/pictures
